      <section id="building-practice">
        <h2>Building a First Principles Practice</h2>
        <p>
          First principles thinking is a skill that develops through practice, not a technique that can be applied once and retained. The cognitive habits it requires — questioning inherited assumptions, distinguishing between physical and organizational constraints, rebuilding from verified foundations — are not natural default modes of human reasoning. They require deliberate cultivation.
        </p>

        <h3>Daily Practice: The Assumption Journal</h3>
        <p>
          Keep a running list of things you "know" in your domain that you've never actually verified. Periodically pick one item from this list and try to derive it from first principles — to trace the belief back to its foundation and verify that the foundation actually holds. You will find, consistently, that some fraction of things you "know" cannot be verified this way. Those are your blind spots and potential opportunities.
        </p>

        <h3>Weekly Practice: The Constraint Audit</h3>
        <p>
          Once per week, identify the constraint that most limits your progress on an important goal. Then ask: is this constraint physical, logical, or mathematical — or is it historical and organizational? If it's the latter, ask what it would take to remove it. Not whether it's practical to remove it right now, but whether it's genuinely necessary. The goal is to build the habit of distinguishing between real and assumed constraints before they compound into permanent limitations.
        </p>

        <h3>The Socratic Partner Practice</h3>
        <p>
          Find a thinking partner — human or AI — who is willing to play the role of systematic questioner. Give them a belief you hold with high confidence and ask them to question it as if they have no investment in whether it's true or false. The questions that make you uncomfortable or that you can't answer easily are the ones worth sitting with. This is how Socrates operated, and it's how the method produces genuine insight rather than just intellectual exercise.
        </p>

        <StepsList>
          <li><strong>Start with a constraint that frustrates you.</strong> First principles thinking is most motivating when the stakes are real — a project that seems stuck, a cost that seems fixed, a problem that everyone says is unsolvable.</li>
          <li><strong>Write down the assumption explicitly.</strong> Name the inherited belief precisely. Vague assumptions can't be examined.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask what would have to be true for this constraint to not exist.</strong> This is the productive reversal — instead of accepting the constraint, ask what its negation would require.</li>
          <li><strong>Research the underlying physics or economics.</strong> What does the thing actually consist of at its most basic level? What do those components cost, require, or involve?</li>
          <li><strong>Identify the gap between the real and assumed constraints.</strong> The gap is the opportunity space.</li>
          <li><strong>Build a minimum viable test.</strong> First principles reasoning produces hypotheses, not certainties. Test the cheapest version of the new solution before committing to it.</li>
        </StepsList>

        <ContentBox type="highlight" title="The Long View">
          <p>First principles thinking is not primarily a technique for solving individual problems. It is a cognitive posture — a sustained orientation toward understanding over knowing, toward deriving over inheriting, toward questioning the foundation before accepting the constraint. Practiced consistently over years, it produces a qualitatively different relationship to uncertainty and complexity: instead of finding constraints frustrating, you find them interesting, because constraints are where the gap between the inherited and the fundamental is most likely to be hiding. The people who have genuinely mastered this approach — Feynman, Musk, Bogle, the great scientists and founders of every era — share this posture more than they share any specific technique. The technique is learnable in a day. The posture takes years. Start today.</p>
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

